occurrences.line_text: For be the fourth with those three other placed:
Deformed monsters, fowle, and blacke as inke,
Sometime a fowle, sometime a fish in lake,
Like a faire Lady, but did fowle Duessa hyde.
Of that fowle euill, which all men reproue,
The fowle Duessa, next vnto the chaire
When two of three her Nephews are so fowle forlorne?
And with her beares the fowle welfauourd witch:
At her abhorred face, so filthy and so fowle.
That name of natiue syre did fowle vpbrayd,
With sonnes owne blade, her fowle reproches spoke;
Scarse could he footing find in that fowle way,
Who after Archimagoes fowle defeat,
And Pholoe fowle, when her to this he doth compaire.
And fly away for feare of fowle disgrace:
With fowle reprochfull words he boldly him defide.
With fowle words tempring faire, soure gall with hony sweet.
All wallowd in his owne fowle bloudy gore,
For ruth of gentle knight so fowle forlore:
But neither darkenesse fowle, nor filthy bands,
And wondred at so fowle deformed wight.
Of fowle Duessa, when her borrowed light
In fowle reproch of knighthoods faire degree,
Farre from that haunt all other chearefull fowle;
With hardie fowle, aboue his hable might,
He could escape fowle death or deadly paines?
Thus fowle to hasten your vntimely date;
He that faire Vna late fowle outraged,
Then fowle reuenging rage, and base contentious iarre.
Of whose fowle deedes, too hideous to be told
Belphoebe fowle forlorne.
As fearefull fowle, that long in secret caue
I home returning, fraught with fowle despight,
But did him deadly daunt, or fowle dismay;
Of griesly hew, and fowle ill fauour'd sight;
Indeede (quoth he) through fowle intemperaunce,
An vgly feend, more fowle then dismall day,
Enwrapped in fowle smoke and clouds more blacke then Iet.
Gaz'd after him, as fowle escapt by flight;
For when Cymochles saw the fowle reproch,
But none then it, more fowle and indecent,
Which when they saw, they weened fowle reproch
But all the liquour, which was fowle and wast,
Prince Arthur them repelles, and fowle
So fowle and vgly, that exceeding feare
Of fowle misshapen wights, of which some were
Slaunderous reproches, and fowle infamies,
To which nor fish nor fowle did once approch,
Or shame, that euer should so fowle defects
Clad in faire weedes, but fowle disordered,
Of her fine fingers, without fowle empeach,
And afterwards they gan with fowle reproch
Nor so fowle outrage doen by liuing men:
After that foster fowle he fiercely rid,
And cast t'auenge him of that fowle despight,
Or else for feare of shame and fowle disgrace.
And thought that match a fowle disparagement:
Forcing to doe, that did him fowle misseeme:
And knighthood fowle defaced by a faithlesse knight.
To do fowle death to dye, or wrap in grieuous woe.
With his late fall, and fowle indignity,
Or else for shame, so fowle reproch to shonne,
That is the father of fowle gealosy,
And with fowle force vnto his will did driue,
Fowle Gealosie, that turnest loue diuine
And oft committed fowle Idolatree.
Yet dread of shame, and doubt of fowle dishonor
Vile treason and fowle falshood hidden were,
Her face most fowle and filthy was to see,
The warie fowle that spies him toward bend
Yet nigh approching, he them fowle bespake,
But often did my folly fowle reproue.
And forst him backe with fowle dishonor to retreat.
If wrathfull wight, then fowle rebuke and shame
From that fowle rudenesse, which did her deface;
They gan remember of the fowle vpbraide,
Most voide of guile, most free from fowle despight,
And horrour of fowle death for Knight vnfit,
Vppon some fowle, that should her feast prepare;
And him to touch with falshoods fowle attaint,
And so great honour with so fowle reproch had blent.
To be auenged for so fowle a deede,
Carried with wings of feare, like fowle aghast,
A dreadfull feend, with fowle deformed looke,
And fowle blasphemous speaches forth did cast,
Breathing out clouds of sulphure fowle and blacke,
Through fowle commixture of his filthy blot;
Gan him salute, and fowle vpbrayd with faulty blame.
And fowle entreaty him indignifyde,
As in despight to be so fowle abused
Of fowle discourtesie, vnfit for Knight;
Because of one, that wrought him fowle despight.
But rather fowler seemed to the eye;
Fled all away for feare of fowler shame.
The bird, that knowes not the false fowlers call,
And now the pray of fowles in field he lyes,
Of fowles and beastes he made the piteous prayes,
Loe, loe alreadie, how the fowles in aire
Of harmefull fowles about them fluttering, cride,
Sitting like King of fowles in maiesty and powre.
And of the fairest late, now made the fowlest place.
Faire knighthood fowly shamed, and doest vaunt
The goddesse wroth gan fowly her disgrace,
A foxes taile, with dong all fowly dight;
For that reprochfull fall right fowly he disdaynd.
And her faire face with teares was fowly blubbered.
The truncked beast fast bleeding, did him fowly dight.
And fowly battered his comely corse,
The famous name of knighthood fowly shend;
Regard of worldly mucke doth fowly blend,
And fowly said, By Mahoune, cursed thiefe,
Both of their life, and fame for euer fowly blent.
Was fowly ra'st, that none the signes might see;
Shall tread adowne, and do him fowly dye,
Yet former feare of being fowly shent,
Of his long labour, he gan fowly wyte
Where they doe wither, and are fowly mard:
Who not content so fowly to deuoure
Ruffled and fowly raid with filthy soyle,
And the faire welkin fowly ouercast,
Was fowly dight, and he of death afeard.
And Florimell him fowly gan reuile,
By the faire lockes, and fowly did array,
First he his beard did shaue, and fowly shent:
She doth subdue, she fowly doth entreate.
That all his former praise doth fowly spill.
That he gainst courtesie so fowly did default.
Else had he surely there bene slaine, or fowlyshent.
She fownd not in that perilous house of Pryde,
Ere long she fownd, whereas he wearie sate,
Where he with his Duessa dalliance fownd,
Of that deare Lord, who oft thereon was fownd,
Yet that, which reft it, no lesse faire was fownd:
Where when confusedly they came, they fownd
Too true the famous Marinell it fownd,
How him in deadly case their Lady fownd,
And then no ods at all in him he fownd:
Sometimes I hunt the Fox, the vowed foe
Now like a foxe, now like a dragon fell,
Into a Foxe himselfe he first did tourne;
But he him hunted like a Foxe full fast:
A foxes taile, with dong all fowly dight;
Sans foy: full large of limbe and euery ioint
Who whiles he liu'de, was called proud Sans foy,
Who when the shamed shield of slaine Sans foy
Euen stout Sans foy (O who can then refrayn?)
Ah deare Sans ioy, next dearest to Sans foy,
And of them both did foy and tribute raise,
And Paynim brethren foyld.
And both his foen with equall foyle to daunt.
Nought else, but treason, from the first this la[n]d did foyle.
Yet all was forg'd and spred with golden foyle,
With golden foyle doth finely ouer spred
And so would hope him easily to foyle.
Whom he did all to peeces breake and foyle
To weet faire Britomart, them late had foyled
We did him leaue, after that he had foyled
He hewd, and lasht, and foynd, and thundred blowes,
And strooke, and foynd, and lasht outrageously,
He stroke, he soust, he foynd, he hewd, he lasht,
She hewd, she foynd, she lasht, she laid on euery side.
But once a man Fradubio, now a tree,
Say on Fradubio then, or man, or tree,
Heard how in vaine Fradubio did lament,
Through which the fragrant Eglantine did spred
And fragrant violets, and Pances trim,
As fresh and fragrant as the floure deluce
And fragrant odours they vppon her threw;
And many battailes fought, and many fraies
And all with suddein indignation fraight,
With the fraile flesh; at last it flitted is,
Both which fraile men do oftentimes mistake,
That my fraile eyes these lines with teares do steepe,
The yron walles to ward their blowes are weake & fraile.
And made wide furrowes in their fleshes fraile,
And mightie strong was turnd to feeble fraile.
Through that fraile fountaine, which him feeble made,
That makes fraile flesh to feare the bitter waue?
Perceiued him to wauer weake and fraile,
Come, come away, fraile, seely, fleshly wight,
And haue her strength recur'd from fraile infirmitis.
Till ruth and fraile affection did constraine,
Else neuer should thy iudgement be so fraile,
How shall fraile pen descriue her heauenly face,
Thereby thine armes seeme stro[n]g, but manhood fraile;
Can call out of the bodies of fraile wightes:
And his fraile eye with spoyle of beautie feedes;
For to allure fraile mind to carelesse ease.
Yet with strong reason maistred passion fraile,
But I, that am fraile flesh and earthly wight,
Like mightie pillours, this fraile life of man,
How shall fraile pen, with feare disparaged,
Of the fraile flesh, relenting to their rage,
Your stubborne hart t'affect with fraile infirmity.
Fraile harts, yet quenched not; like starry light
Sad, solemne, sowre, and full of fancies fraile
Now ranckleth in this same fraile fleshly mould,
But if the passion mayster thy fraile might,
Least his fraile senses were emperisht quight,
Fraile Ladies hart with loues consuming rage,
In her fraile wit, that now her quite forlore:
The whiles the passing brightnes her fraile sences dazed.
And the fraile soule in deepe delight nigh dround:
By which fraile youth is oft to follie led,
Amongst fraile men, that many a publike state
But there it present was, and did fraile sense entice.
And did him selfe from fraile impatience refraine.
Of my fraile safetie, resting in the might
They fall too short of our fraile reckonings,
To her fraile mansion of mortality.
From things, that stirre vp fraile affection;
Are bound with commun bond of frailtee,
For he was flesh: (all flesh doth frailtie breed.)
The one faire fram'd of burnisht Yuory,
And fram'd of liquid ayre her tender partes
In deepest Hell, and framd by Furies skill,
Some framd faire lookes, glancing like euening lights,
But of more worthy substance fram'd it was;
Of that same wood it fram'd was cunningly,
This mischiefe framd, for their first loues defeature,
On stately pillours, fram'd after the Doricke guize.
Or could be fram'd by workmans rare deuice;
(Let none them read) thereof did verses frame,
And thinking of those braunches greene to frame
And fitting gestures to her purpose frame;
That on a staffe his feeble steps did frame,
For he had charge my discipline to frame,
His mortall life he learned had to frame
Yet is Cleopolis for earthly frame,
On which they lowly sit, and fitting purpose frame.
Therefore this craftie engine he did frame,
And wondrous strong by nature, and by skilfull frame.
Whilest she her selfe thus busily did frame,
That vnto thee due worship I may rightly frame.
His stedfast life, and all his actions frame,
That quite disparted all the linked frame,
The frame thereof seemd partly circulare,
To vew her castles other wondrous frame.
That Turrets frame most admirable was,
That goodly frame from ruine to sustaine:
Now gins this goodly frame of Temperance
The skilfull Palmer formally did frame.
To which her steps directly she did frame.
Whereto that single knight did answere frame;
Long were it to describe the goodly frame,
And hostes of men of meanest things could frame,
And diuerse plots did frame, to maske in strange disguise.
To youre faire selues a faire ensample frame,
She there deuiz'd a wondrous worke to frame,
For he could well his glozing speaches frame
But yet what so my feeble Muse can frame,
Of gracious speach, and skill his words to frame
But leasure had, and libertie to frame
Th'Enchaunter selfe, which all that fraud did frame,
To see their thrids so thin, as spiders frame,
This goodly counterfesaunce he did frame.
But by no meanes they could it thereto frame.
Frame thunderbolts for Ioues auengefull threate.
To frame such subtile wire, so shinie cleare.
Her mournefull notes full piteously did frame,
And causelesse crimes continually to frame,
And all the seruice of the bodie frame,
And costly frame, were long here to relate.
Could frame in earth, and forme of substance base,
I much admyring that so goodly frame,
The fertile Nile, which creatures new doth frame;
To whom the elder did this aunswere frame;
Which she against the dred Mercilla oft did frame.
And of his owne vaine fancies thought did frame:
Which though I be not wise enough to frame,
By speaking signes, as he them best could frame;
Endure to trauell, nor one foote to frame:
He to that point fit speaches gan to frame,
With that him selfe to battell he did frame;
And to recomfort him, all comely meanes did frame.
Faire Vna framed words and count'nance fit:
It framed was, one massie entire mould,
Against Pyrrochles, and new matter framed
Framed of wanton Yuie, flouring faire,
Trees, braunches, birds, and songs were framed fit,
Yt framed was of precious yuory,
Which all of purest bullion framed were,
His maker with her charmes had framed him so well.
Whose like on earth was neuer framed yit,
Framed in goldsmithes forge with cunning hand:
And framed speaches fit for his behoofe,
Nor that, which that wise King of Iurie framed,
And men themselues, the which at first were framed
The which was framed all of siluer fine,
Built a faire Chappell, and an Altar framed
The flesh of men, to Gods owne likenesse framed,
Vntill that, whether wicked fate so framed,
Into old Gall, that now is cleeped France,
To whom the world this franchise euer yeelded,
To weet to worke Irenaes franchisement,
Ten times so much be numbred francke and free.
Where them does meete a francklin faire and free,
Franckly each paramour his leman knowes,
Thereto they both did franckly condiscend,
Might not be found a franker franion,
But some fayre Franion, fit for such a fere,
More franke affection did to her afford,
Of their franke loues, free from all gealous spyes:
In doing gentle deedes with franke delight,
Might frankely there their loues desire possesse;
Which fuming all with frankensence I found,
Might not be found a franker franion,
They all perfumde with frankincense diuine,
Whiles th'altars fume with frankincense arownd,
Or Cybeles franticke rites haue made them mad;
Who all enrag'd with smart and franticke yre,
What franticke fit (quoth he) hath thus distraught
But when the franticke fit inflamd his spright,
Her franticke sonne, and kindles his courage,
And loue to frenzy turnd, sith loue is franticke hight.
With franticke passion, and with furie fraught;
As a mad bytch, when as the franticke fit
Beware of fraud, beware of ficklenesse,
For feare least Force or Fraud should vnaware
Th'Enchaunter selfe, which all that fraud did frame,
Ne each of other feared fraud or tort,
Farre from all fraud, or fayned blandishment;
Some fearing fraud, some fraudulently fayning,
Of force, ne fraud in wight was to be found:
Like treacherous, like full of fraud and guile,
And him doth chyde as false and fraudulent,
Some fearing fraud, some fraudulently fayning,
For he was false, and fraught with ficklenesse,
By this sad Vna fraught with anguish sore,
With windy Nitre and quick Sulphur fraught,
Then fraught with rancour, and engorged ire,
I home returning, fraught with fowle despight,
Which when his brother saw, fraught with great griefe
Glad was the knight, & with fresh courage fraught,
And forth together went, with sorrow fraught.
The Gardins of Adonis fraught
From her sweet bowres, and beds with pleasures fraught:
And causde great sackes with endlesse riches fraught,
Hauing the mindes of men with fury fraught,
Then vp she rose fraught with melancholy,
Wherewith the Souldan all with furie fraught,
With franticke passion, and with furie fraught;
Therewith, all fraught with fury and disdaine,
Out of her poysnous entrails, fraught with dire decay.
The other held a snake with venime fraught,
Till fortune fraught with malice, blinde, and brute,
But then the Captaine fraught with more displeasure,
Whereof her wombe vnwist to wight was fraught,
Whose father Hercules in Fraunce did quell,
With foule repulse from Fraunce was forced to retire.
The bowels of wide Fraunce, a forlorne Dame,
Besides subiected Fraunce, and Germany,
The shaking Palsey, and Saint Fraunces fire:
To aide his friends, or fray his enimies:
And bad her knight addresse him to the fray:
Disdaind to loose the meed he wonne in fray,
And sight of men, since his late luckelesse fray.
And much reioyced in their bloudy fray:
So diuersly themselues in vaine they fray;
Some troublous vprore or contentious fray,
Of mightie GÃ¶emot, whom in stout fray
When so him list his enimies to fray:
Then when they were accorded from the fray,
And there the relicks of the drunken fray,
Was set, to see the fortune of that fray,
By her subdewed in victorious fray:
He to her told the story of that fray,
For her beginning a more fearefull fray,
There then began a fearefull cruell fray
To weet the cause of so vncomely fray,
When the bold Centaures made that bloudy fray
That who them sees, would wonder at their fray,
Tho when as he was dead, the fray gan ceasse,
But as a man, whom hellish feends haue frayd,
That could haue frayd one with the very sight,
He ran at him enrag[e]d in stead of being frayde.
The Lyon frayed them, him in to let:
What frayes ye, that were wont to comfort me affrayd?
But in vaine glorious frayes he litle did delight.
Had doen to death, subdewde in equall frayes,
Sweare she is yours, and stirre vp bloudie frayes,
In stead of fraying, they them selues did feare,
Captiu'd to fortune and frayle worldly feares,
Their frayle amazed senses did confound:
That his frayle thighes nigh wearie and fordonne
And in frayle wood on Adrian gulfe doth fleet,
Frayle men are oft captiu'd to couetise:
In frayle intemperance through sinfull bayt;
Deepe indignation and compassion frayle
And pardon her besought his errour frayle,
All flesh is frayle, and full of ficklenesse,
To suppliants, through frayltie which offend.
Through enuies snares or fortunes freakes vnkind:
O but I feare the fickle freakes (quoth shee)
So tossed was in fortunes cruell freakes;
And knitting all his force got one hand free,
And when he sate vpon his courser free,
Full strongly armd, and on a courser free,
Those keyes, and made himselfe free enterance.
Raunging the forest wide on courser free,
But he him forst to stay, and tellen free
In all affaires, and was both bold and free,
Or free his feet, that in the myre sticke fast?
Where them does meete a francklin faire and free,
Of God, of grace, of iustice, of free will,
He did supply their want, and gaue them euer free.
Which comming downe to ground, does free it selfe by fight.
Therefore since mine he is, or free or bond,
That long captiued soules from wearie thraldome free.
To chaunge thy will, and set Occasion free,
Loe there they be; to thee I yield them free.
When euer his fiers hands he free mote find:
Ten times so much be numbred francke and free.
Lo see soone after, how more bold and free
Now were they liegemen to this Lady free,
In his free thought to build her sluggish nest:
The heauens so fauourable were and free,
From perill free he her away did beare:
But when he saw himselfe free from poursute,
And to be free from hard restraint and gealous feares.
Their garments wet, and weary armour free,
And to thy will abuse? Thou walkest free,
Their purpost flight, free from all mens reclame;
That did her win and free from chalenge set:
For Loue is free, and led with selfe delight,
Not all the gods can chaunge, nor Ioue him self can free.
And louely haulst from feare of treason free,
Consent, that I who stood all fearelesse free,
All which he did from bitter bondage free,
The faire Poeana he enlarged free;
Then hearke ye gentle knights and Ladies free,
That in this ioyous place they mote haue ioyance free.
That being free from feare and gealosye,
From which vnlesse some heauenly powre her free
Most voide of guile, most free from fowle despight,
So had I rather to be thrall, then free;
The which the prisoner points vnto the free,
Together with her selfe in dowry free;
Yet would she not thereto yeeld free accord,
And by his freedome get his free goodwill;
That in and out thou mayst haue passage free.
Promist, if she would free him from that case,
Had shrowded bene, she did from thraldome free;
Free Samient from feare:
Most sacred wight, most debonayre and free,
Of Artegals arryuall, her to free,
But I that knew my selfe from perill free,
Yet shall it not her lockes for raunsome fro me free.
Of their franke loues, free from all gealous spyes:
Since first he saw her, and did free from feare
For that him selfe he thought from daunger free,
From whom he meant to free him, if he might,
And whether free with him she now were, or in band.
Whom when the Saluage saw from daunger free,
But turne we now backe to that Ladie free,
She was borne free, not bound to any wight,
Leading a life so free and fortunate,
Simple and true from couert malice free:
From blamefull blot, and free from all that wite,
Henceforth his ghost freed from repining strife,
By which he freed the Traueilers high way,
Her selfe freed from that foster insolent,
Which I your vassall, by your prowesse freed,
And eke fayre Amoret now freed from feare,
Who being freed, from one a weapon fiercely takes.
My Amoret, sith you her freed fro thence,
Her freed, in which ye her all hopelesse left,
Now freed from feare and danger of that dismall wight.
Who being freed from Proteus cruell band
But he him selfe full lightly from him freed,
So when that Knight from perill cleare was freed,
That yet my loue may from their hands be freed.
So hauing freed Irena from distresse,
Whom from her Seneschall he lately freed,
Which had them freed from that deadly feare,
That like an Hauke, which feeling her selfe freed
By Calepine is freed.
That of their loues choise they might freedom clame,
Whose freedome shall thee turne to greatest scath.
Or his exchange, or freedome might be wrought.
Could she her wished freedome fro me wooe;
Such thraldome or such freedome let it surely be.
And vncontrolled freedome to obtaine.
Spighting my happie freedome, haue agreed,
And by his freedome get his free goodwill;
Life, freedome, grace, and gifts of great auaile,
Vnto her Queene, his freedome to haue gayned;
And him she told, her Dame his freedome did denye.
Vntill his owne true loue his freedome gayned,
Were turnd, and they to freedome did retyre.
For freeing from their snares Irena thrall:
Yet shall they not escape so freely all;
Till from her cursed foe thou haue her freely quit.
And freely sprong out of the fruitfull ground,
But in a body, which doth freely yeeld
As freely offering to be gathered:
And freely read, what wicked felon so
All is his iustly, that all freely dealth:
Now freely drew, and found right safe assurance theare.
Fearing least if she should him freely set,
